Okay... here's the re-thought about undead army rules.


-If they win a battle, they get a 75% chance per each dead enemy to turn that
dead enemy into a member of their own ranks.  (ie: If a knight died in the
battle, there is a 75% chance that the undead army will get a knight added
to their ranks.)

-There is no maintenace cost for undead.

-There is one undead castle that is the only place undead nobles can be
 formed or learn skills.  If this castle is taken over by a player, it
 will automatically be destroyed and a new one will appear in a random
 location on the map. (So they can be a constant threat.) The player who
 is the first player in the castle when it is taken over but before it
 is destroyed gets a whole bunch (5? 10? 20?) noble points for being
 so brave and risking so many troops.

-Undead nobles automatically know how to sail "ghost ships".  Ghost ships
 can be created by an undead noble and they can carry up to 100 undead
 troops (including nobles) (undead don't weigh anything)  Since ghost
 ships are etheral, they always sail at full speed regardless of wind
 condition (they need no rowers). 

-Undead nobles cost 2 noble points. All the time.

-Undead get a noble point for pillaging a city. They also get a random amount
 of undead troops.

-Undead get a noble point when they win a battle. 

-Undead DO NOT get a "standard" noble point per turn. (This means they have
 to constantly be attacking things to get noble points.

-Undead nobles automatically know all of the necromancy spells

-Undead nobles (when in the "Castle of the Undead" can spend time and
 noble points (if nessecary) to learn other magic skills.) Undead nobles
 will not need to know "normal" skills such as beastmastery or construction
 for example.

-Undead noble can not be ill and they will not heal naturally, they can
only heal through the use of a "healing" spell.

Well, what do you think?

Here's some ideas for necromancy spells:

-Summon undead soldiers:  Cost=1np, The caster gains 2d6 undead soldiers.

-Summon undead archers: Cost=1np, The caster gains 1d6 undead archers.

-Summon undead knights: Cost=2np, The caster gains 1d6 undead knights.

-Summon undead horse: Cost=1np, The caster gains 1 undead horse that can
 carry 150 units of wieght. (Mainly for carrying himself on)

-Bannish undead: Cost=1np, 2d6 undead men from the target unit are destroyed.
 
-Destroy undead: Cost=2np, 4d6 undead men from the target unit are destroyed.

-Summon Ghost ship: Cost=2np, a ghost ship will appear and the summoning unit
 oops, I mean noble, will be placed inside along with all his men and anyone
 stacked with him.  If all undead nobles leave a ghost ship, it will disapear.
 The summoning noble isn't really the captain of the ship, ths ship comes
 with an undead captain and crew.  When all nobles leave the ship, the captain
 sails his ship away.  A captain will follow orders from any undead noble though
 so as long as one noble remains on board, the ship won't disapear.

I didn't include aura points. I think that undead nobles should be able to
cast necromantic spells without using aura since they are magic in the
first place.  They'd have to use aura to cast other kinds of spells though.

You'd have to spread special weapons around that only nobles can use. They'd
have special bonus vs. undead.  Undead can't pick these weapons up, they
would have to be droped if someone with one of them was killed.  Human
nobles will never surrender to the undead, they'll keep fighting to the
last man. (In that case, maybe that 75% chance of becoming undead should
be reduced to 50
-oops-
be reduced to 50%.  That would be a bit more fair.



Well, what do you think so far?  If you like this and want to hand control 
of an undead army over to me, I'll be happy to think of some more cool
undead rules.



Oh yeah... undead will never surrender either. They'll fight to the
last man... erm... corpse. :)

-Greg

