Yes... graveyards!!  There can be only 10 undead nobles at a time.
When one dies, the controller (me I guess) issues a FORM command and
the specific graveyard that the undead noble will rise from.  Undead
nobles always rise with 10 (?) undead. (that way, they won't be killed
off so quickly as soon as they rise.)  When undead rise and there are
living in the graveyard they rose from, all men (not nobles) must make
a panic test. Each man has a 50% chance of fleeing (leaving the nobles
invintory). Also, each turn a living noble is in a graveyard, there is
a 2% chance of him being grabbed by the feet by skeletal hands and
being pulled under. (That way, a huge army won't just hang out in
the graveyard waiting for undead nobles to arise.)

How about when undead nobles rise from the grave, they automatically cast
a free summon undead soldiers and a free summon undead archer spell. That
way, if a living noble was hanging around a graveyard with troops, he
wouldn't just be able to automatically kill the lone undead noble.

Generate 1 NP every time they pillage also (If they collected at least
7 undead during the pillaging?)

They automatically attack everyone they meet.

The necromancy spells I sugjested would be for anyone wanting to study them,
not just undead.

If a ghost ship is attacked, it can protect 100 undead (instead of 50)
and the ship itself cannot be damaged.  If a ghost ship attacks, the
same rules apply I guess.  That way, it would be VERY unwise to venture
out on the sea if it's being haunted.

Maybe add summon undead (any type of unit except elites) to the necromantic
spells.  

Type summoned           NP cost         number summoned
Soldiers		1		3d6
Pike			1		2d6
Swordsmen		1		1d6
Archers			1		1d6
Crossbowmen		1		2d6
Knights			2		1d6

I didn't put Aura cost in cuz I don't know the scale of aura. Know what I mean?
Undead wouldn't have to expend aura anyways. They auto know all necromantic
spells at Grand Master level (or whatever the highest is) and they can't
learn any other types of spells anyways.

Maybe more to come later.  What do you think?

-Greg



